<article class="post--single post-798 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-drinks category-dairy-free category-gluten-free category-summer category-vegan category-vegetarian tag-booze tag-london tag-pimms ingredients-pimms" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="kicker">
      <time class="updated" datetime="2010-07-23T21:00:00+00:00">Friday, July 23, 2010</time>
    </div>
    <h1 class="title" >
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/07/thats-the-spirit/">That&#8217;s the spirit</a>
    </h1>
  </header>
  <div class="post-content" itemprop="articleBody">
    <p>I hope you know that I take my job seriously. A number of you asked for a Pimm‚Äôs Cup recipe, so I‚Äôve been drinking a lot of it. Just for you.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/9287f-4816877805_3cf10cd705_z1.jpg"><img decoding="async" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5496584631025328578" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/9287f-4816877805_3cf10cd705_z1.jpg?w=295" alt="" width="630" height="640" border="0" /></a><br />
That‚Äôs Brandon‚Äôs hand there, and actually, he‚Äôs holding a gin and tonic, but it doesn‚Äôt matter. The gesture is what counts. Long live Pimm‚Äôs Cup! Cheers!</p>
<p>I first tasted <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pimm%27s">Pimm‚Äôs</a> in its native city of London, where it came to the table in a pitcher, mixed with fizzy lemonade to a handsome shade of amber. There were slices of cucumber, lemon, and strawberry floating among the ice cubes, and a sprig of mint, and it was very hot outside, very hot, and after I drank a glass of it, I had one of the finest summer afternoons in memory. I cannot prove that the two events were causally related, but in my personal catalog of experiences, they‚Äôre on the same page. I keep thinking that somehow, if I drink enough Pimm‚Äôs, I‚Äôll wind up back in London, or in an episode of <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u-BAUG97gZo">Jeeves and Wooster</a>, but I usually just wind up falling asleep early, fully clothed, forgetting to brush my teeth, in Seattle.</p>
<p>I get the sense that a lot of you have had Pimm‚Äôs, but for those of you who haven‚Äôt, it‚Äôs a gin-based drink containing quinine &#8211; the substance that gives tonic water its bitter flavor &#8211; and various herbs, and probably a bunch of other ingredients, though the formula is a secret. It was made to serve as a digestif, but few drink it straight. On its own, it‚Äôs quite intense, with a flavor that combines citrus and spice with a little burnt caramel. On its own, it tastes like Christmas, only bitter. It tastes like the Christmas when I was fifteen, when I had the flu and my mother gave me a plaid flannel dress and a belt made from recycled car tires and bottle caps, and I cried when she asked me to try it on. Needless to say, Pimm‚Äôs is best mixed, if you ask me, and that‚Äôs how it‚Äôs most commonly served. Once mixed, it mellows considerably. It‚Äôs bright, refreshing, embarrassingly easy to drink. The British mix it most often with what they call lemonade, though it‚Äôs not the same thing as American lemonade; it‚Äôs a clear, sparkling lemon soda, and it‚Äôs sweet, but not too sweet. In the States, a decent substitute is 7-Up, or Sprite. It‚Äôs also acceptable to mix it with ginger ale or ginger beer.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/fc7af-pimmsandginger-11.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5496844698332542914" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/fc7af-pimmsandginger-11.jpg?w=294" alt="" width="1566" height="1600" border="0" /></a><br />
Except that I don‚Äôt really care for that ginger ale up there, Reed‚Äôs Extra Ginger Brew, in my Pimm‚Äôs Cup. I meant to buy Reed‚Äôs <span style="font-style: italic;">Original</span> Ginger Brew. Until I took that picture, I didn‚Äôt realize that I had bought the wrong kind. In any case, Reed&#8217;s is a good grocery-store bet, but if you&#8217;re in Seattle and have access to <a href="http://rachelsgingerbeer.com/" target="_blank">Rachel&#8217;s Ginger Beer</a>, for god&#8217;s sake, use that. It&#8217;s the best.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/f84e0-pimmsalone1.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5496847929472974178" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/f84e0-pimmsalone1.jpg?w=293" alt="" width="1561" height="1600" border="0" /></a><br />
At any rate, there are a lot of possibilities when it comes to making a Pimm‚Äôs-based cocktail, and you can find many of them <a href="http://www.spittoon.biz/pimms_and_pimms_based_cocktail.html">here</a>, or on <a href="http://www.anyoneforpimms.com/">the official Pimm‚Äôs website</a>, which I‚Äôm crazy for. To get into the site, on the page where you input your birth date, the ‚Äúsubmit‚Äù button doesn‚Äôt just say ‚Äúsubmit,‚Äù but instead ‚ÄúTally ho, IN we go!‚Äù That‚Äôs the spirit! Then, once you‚Äôre in, the home page treats you to a video of a pitcher being filled &#8211; mysteriously, benevolently, from an unseen hand above &#8211; with ice, Pimm‚Äôs, lemonade, and fruit, all of it splashing around and catching the sunlight in a relentlessly juicy way, so mesmerizing that I‚Äôve hit ‚Äúreload‚Äù on the Pimm‚Äôs website six times since I started writing this sentence.</p>
<p>This to say that I‚Äôve been reading up on Pimm‚Äôs, and doing my homework, and in the name of research, I‚Äôve made Pimm‚Äôs cocktails six different ways in the past few weeks. I‚Äôve tried Pimm‚Äôs with 7-Up, Reed‚Äôs Original Ginger Brew, Reed‚Äôs Premium Ginger Brew, Reed‚Äôs Extra Ginger Brew, San Pellegrino Limonata, and, finally, a mixture of American lemonade and sparkling water. Whatever you mix it with, it‚Äôs standard to use 1 part Pimm‚Äôs to 3 parts mixer, and that‚Äôs what I‚Äôve done. Plus slices of lemon and cucumber, and a slice of strawberry, and mint.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/df6ce-4816879953_52f91efe15_z1.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5496584639621297362" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/df6ce-4816879953_52f91efe15_z1.jpg?w=295" alt="" width="630" height="640" border="0" /></a><br />
All told, and with apologies to any lemonade or 7-Up die-hards out there, I like my Pimm‚Äôs best with ginger beer. It‚Äôs a little more complex, a little less sweet, and with a squeeze of lemon, it‚Äôs what I‚Äôm going to be drinking for the rest of the summer, starting tonight. Happy Friday.</p>

<section id="recipe-1" class="recipe" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Recipe">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="kicker">Recipe</div>
    <h2 class="title" itemprop="name">My Pimm‚Äôs Cup</h2>
        <meta itemprop="author" content="Molly">
    <meta itemprop="published" content="2010-07-23T21:00:00-04:00">
  </header>

      <figure class="hero">
          </figure>
  
  <div class="recipe-intro" itemprop="summary">
    <nav class="recipe-utility-nav">
      <a href="/2010/07/thats-the-spirit/?print_recipe=1" class="print icon-print"></a>
    </nav>
    <p>The recipe below is for one serving, but to make a pitcher, just scale up accordingly, keeping the 1:3 ratio of Pimm‚Äôs to ginger beer.</p>
  </div>

      <div class="recipe-list">
                                <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            1 ¬Ω ounces Pimm‚Äôs No. 1
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            4 ¬Ω ounces ginger ale or ginger beer
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            Ice
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            1 thin slice cucumber
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            1 thin slice lemon, plus more for squeezing
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            1 slice strawberry
          </div>
                  <div class="ingredient" itemprop="ingredients">
            A couple of mint leaves          </div>
                  </div>
  
      <div itemprop="instructions">
      <p>Combine the Pimm‚Äôs and ginger beer in a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collins_glass">Collins glass</a>, or something similar. Add ice until the liquid comes almost to the rim of the glass. Add the cucumber, lemon, and strawberry, plus a small squeeze of lemon juice, if you like. Use a straw to bash the fruit around a little bit. Add the mint, and serve immediately.</p>
    </div>
  
      <p itemprop="yield">Yield: 1 drink</p>
  </section>

  </div>
